sparql_query_kg2:
To produce a SPARQL query for KG2 (OpenAlex) based on the given information, we need to translate the DBLP query into the OpenAlex ontology. The DBLP query is:

```sparql
SELECT DISTINCT ?answer WHERE { 
  ?answer <https://dblp.org/rdf/schema#authoredBy> <https://dblp.org/pid/00/6329> } 
UNION { 
  ?answer <https://dblp.org/rdf/schema#authoredBy> <https://dblp.org/pid/04/7485> } 
}
```

Given the entity and relation mapping (ER2) provided, we can see that:

- For Andr\u00E9 Kaup, the DBLP PID `00/6329` maps to an ORCID ID of `0000-0002-0929-5074` in OpenAlex.
- For C. Lin, the DBLP PID `04/7485` maps to an ORCID ID of `0000-0003-2847-0349` in OpenAlex.
- The relation `<https://dblp.org/rdf/schema#authoredBy>` in DBLP maps to `oa:hasAuthorship` in OpenAlex, and `oa:hasAuthor` in OpenAlex.

Here is the translated SPARQL query for OpenAlex:

```sparql
<sparql>
PREFIX oa: <https://semopenalex.org/ontology/>

SELECT DISTINCT ?work
WHERE {
  ?work oa:hasAuthorship ?authorship1 .
  ?authorship1 oa:hasAuthor ?author1 .
  ?author1 <https://dbpedia.org/ontology/orcidId> "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0929-5074" .

  { 
    ?work oa:hasAuthorship ?authorship2 .
    ?authorship2 oa:hasAuthor ?author2 .
    ?author2 <https://dbpedia.org/ontology/orcidId> "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2847-0349" .
  }

  UNION { 
    ?work oa:hasAuthorship ?authorship2 .
    ?authorship2 oa:hasAuthor ?author2 .
    ?author2 <https://dbpedia.org/ontology/orcidId> "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2847-0349" .
  }
}
</sparql>
```

This query finds the papers authored by Andr\u00E9 Kaup (ORCID: `0000-0002-0929-5074`) and C. Lin (ORCID: `0000-0003-2847-0349`) in the OpenAlex knowledge graph.

